Principal Component Analysis

Dataset t(protein_data_PCA)

This dataset contains 24 individuals and 1324 variables.

1. Study of the outliers

The analysis of the graphs does not detect any outlier.

2. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of PCA express 56.81% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 56.81% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is relatively high and thus the first plane well represents the data variability. This value is strongly greater than the reference value that equals 10.87%, the variability explained by this plane is thus highly significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 456 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it should be better to also interpret the dimensions greater or equal to the third one.

Figure 2 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the PCA

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 5 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (78.94% against 26.01%). This observation suggests that only these axis are carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

3. Description of the plane 1:2

Figure 3.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction.

Figure 3.2 - Variables factor map (PCA) The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as HG001_RPMI_BR2_t4h, ST1258_RPMI_BR1_t4h and HG001_RPMI_BR3_t4h (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as HG001_TSB_BR3_t4h, HG001_TSB_BR1_t4h, HG001_TSB_BR2_t4h, ST1258_TSB_BR3_t4h and ST1258_TSB_BR1_t4h (to the left of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals HG001_RPMI_BR2_t4h, ST1258_RPMI_BR1_t4h and HG001_RPMI_BR3_t4h stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for variables like leuA, msrA2, SAOUHSC_02702, pepT, mepR, metQ1, thyA, cntA, SAOUHSC_01408 and trxB (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for variables like uvrA, SAOUHSC_01966, SAOUHSC_01664, cdd, sdaAA, SAOUHSC_02846, era, SAOUHSC_01649, sufT and SAOUHSC_01974 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The group in which the individuals HG001_TSB_BR3_t4h, HG001_TSB_BR1_t4h, HG001_TSB_BR2_t4h, ST1258_TSB_BR3_t4h and ST1258_TSB_BR1_t4h stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for variables like thiE, fadB, fadD, acsA, sucB, nanA, SAOUHSC_02425, mqo1, clfA and putA (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for variables like rpmC, rpsC, rplA, rplQ, rplV, rplX, rplF, rpmA, udk and rplJ (variables are sorted from the weakest).

Note that the variables cmk, gnd, groES, guaA, hemE, lysS, map, murE, rpoA and sstD are highly correlated with this dimension (respective correlation of 0.91, 0.93, 0.94, 0.9, 0.9, 0.97, 0.92, 0.9, 0.91, 0.93, 0.93, 0.92, 0.9, 0.91, 0.93). These variables could therefore summarize themselve the dimension 1.

The dimension 2 opposes individuals such as ST1258_TSB_BR2_exp, HG001_TSB_BR2_exp, ST1258_TSB_BR3_exp, ST1258_TSB_BR1_exp and HG001_TSB_BR1_exp (to the top of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as HG001_TSB_BR3_t4h, HG001_TSB_BR1_t4h, HG001_RPMI_BR2_t4h, HG001_TSB_BR2_t4h, ST1258_TSB_BR3_t4h, ST1258_RPMI_BR1_t4h, HG001_RPMI_BR3_t4h and ST1258_TSB_BR1_t4h (to the bottom of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals ST1258_TSB_BR2_exp, HG001_TSB_BR2_exp, ST1258_TSB_BR3_exp, ST1258_TSB_BR1_exp and HG001_TSB_BR1_exp stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for variables like SAOUHSC_01716, ssaA, SAOUHSC_01717, tagH, SAOUHSC_01700, SAOUHSC_01979, scpA, cshA, SAOUHSC_01454 and def2 (variables are sorted from the strongest).

Note that the variables SAOUHSC_01700, SAOUHSC_01979 and ssaA are highly correlated with this dimension (respective correlation of 0, 0.02, 0.01). These variables could therefore summarize themselve the dimension 2.

6. Classification

Figure 6 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 3 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals such as HG001_TSB_BR1_t4h, HG001_TSB_BR2_t4h, HG001_TSB_BR3_t4h, ST1258_TSB_BR1_t4h, ST1258_TSB_BR2_t4h and ST1258_TSB_BR3_t4h. This group is characterized by :

  • variables whose values do not differ significantly from the mean.

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as HG001_TSB_BR1_exp, HG001_TSB_BR2_exp, ST1258_TSB_BR1_exp, ST1258_TSB_BR2_exp and ST1258_TSB_BR3_exp. This group is characterized by :

  • variables whose values do not differ significantly from the mean.

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as HG001_RPMI_BR2_t4h, HG001_RPMI_BR3_t4h and ST1258_RPMI_BR1_t4h. This group is characterized by :

  • variables whose values do not differ significantly from the mean.
